   <h1>Re: [T2] brake upgrade on a '72 westy</h1>
   <b>Paul Manning &lt;paulmanning97_at_yahoo_dot_com&gt;</b><br/>
   <i>2006-06-19 05:40:24+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>hey folks.  Another really long post.  Sorry.

This is a reply to a post from 3 years ago, that applies to my
situation.  So, I had that issue with the locked-up rear wheel a couple
of weeks ago, and that got me thinking about my brakes.  I've been
stopping fine, but I haven't really gotten into the front (disk) brakes
to see what was up.  With a plan to go camping next weekend, I thought
it wise to replace the pads or at least see how the old ones looked. 
After wrestling the driver's side pads out, the piston on the
inner-side won't go back.  If that was the only issue, it wouldn't be
so bad.  The disk has a lot of rust on it, and the rubber boot on the
piston is torn up.  I figured I could take the disk to a machinist and
get it fixed (unless its too hosed), or I could just acquire new
not-rusty parts.  I thought the same of the calipers - you know what
you have if its all new.... this backstory gets me to my reply to this
3 year old thread below.
First, Paul, if you're out there, did you change your brakes from '72
to '73-'79?  From looking at the busDepot offerings, they consider the
72-79 backing plates the same, and I can't find a reference for a
spindle.  I figured that the caliper and rotor needed to be the same,
but perhaps the other 2 items were not needed for the '72 upgrade, but
necessary for a non-disk to disk upgrade.  Lyle?  Anyone? 

My thinking:
- my rotors probably can't be machined true - the damage is too great,
and the rust is too severe.
- I can stay '72 with new rotors ($60ea) and rebuilt calipers ($80ea)
for $300 or upgrade to '73/9 new rotors ($50ea) and new calipers
($100ea) for $300.

Basically, I'm out $300 either way I go, and I'd replace the rubber
lines in the front while I had the system open.  I figure brakes that
had the benefit of more engineering are probably better if the price
truly is the same.  The real question is:  do I really need more than
the rotors and calipers?  Any stories or issues on the rebuilt calipers
for the 71/2?

I really appreciate your help, and I'll miss your posts, Mr. Hineline.

Paul Manning
Lake Oswego, OR
1972 Westy (hapy)</pre>


